    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For metric.csv: group by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute (a) total row count, (b) global P50 and P95 of the 'value' column using the full series, and (c) within the incident window 2024-01-24 04:08:41 to 2024-01-24 04:38:41 UTC (use pd.to_datetime(timestamp, unit='s', utc=True) for filtering) compute count_in_window, earliest timestamp_in_window, latest timestamp_in_window. Return the result table limited to top 20 rows sorted by total count, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_total, p50_value, p95_value, count_in_window, first_ts_in_window, last_ts_in_window. For trace.csv: do the same grouping by (cmdb_id, trace_name) with the same aggregated columns (using 'value' field for p50/p95). For log.csv: group by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute the same aggregated columns (use 'value' for p50/p95). For error_logs.csv: group by cmdb_id and compute count_total and count_in_window and earliest and latest timestamps in window; return top 20 cmdb_id rows by total count. Also return a compact list of unique cmdb_id values present across all four files. Do not print full raw time series—only the aggregated tables described above." }

{
    "analysis": "From the aggregated telemetry results we know: (1) the top metric/trace/log groups each have full coverage across the incident window (samples from 2024-01-24T04:11:00Z to 2024-01-24T04:35:00Z, count 25). (2) No error_log entries were found in the aggregated error_logs.csv for the window. (3) Metric p50/p95 values are available per component-KPI (e.g., ts-voucher-service socket p95=4, many admin-* and travel-* services have cpu/diskio/mem/socket/latency KPIs). (4) Trace p50/p95 and error_rate summaries show non-zero durations and row_count across many services but trace error_rate p95 values shown are 0 for many root->service edges. Given this, the next step is metric-based anomaly detection to find which component-KPI series breached their global thresholds during the incident window (high-side anomalies such as >=P95, and also low-side anomalies such as <=P5 for traffic/business KPIs). We must compute global thresholds using the full series (not filtered) and then look for anomalies inside the incident window; afterward we will use traces and logs to disambiguate candidates. No root cause can be declared yet without identifying metric faults first.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) do the following: (a) compute global P95 and global P5 of 'value' using the full available series for that group (do not filter by time), (b) filter the original metric points to the incident window 2024-01-24 04:08:41 → 2024-01-24 04:38:41 UTC, (c) within the window detect anomalies of two types: high anomalies where value >= P95, and low anomalies where value <= P5. For each group report a compact summary row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_value, p5_value, anomaly_type (high/low), count_anomalies_in_window, first_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, last_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, and severity_metric where severity_metric = (max_value_in_window - p95_value)/p95_value for high anomalies or (p5_value - min_value_in_window)/p5_value for low anomalies. Return up to top 20 rows sorted by count_anomalies_in_window (desc) then severity_metric (desc). Do not print raw time series rows—only the aggregated summary table described above."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed preprocess -> anomaly detection for the five candidate services and derived a focused set of metric, trace, and log anomalies inside the incident window. Key deductions so far: (1) ts-order-service shows the strongest metric spikes (latency-50 with very high relative severity ~3.8, plus CPU and disk I/O spikes), indicating a substantial performance fault. (2) ts-auth-service and ts-route-service show notable drops in log.row_count (reduced throughput) and some metric spikes in auth, but their metric severities are smaller than order's latency spike. (3) Trace error rates are zero across the board, so we cannot rely on trace error_rate to point to failure; we must use trace latencies to order events temporally and determine call-chain ordering. (4) No error_log entries exist for the five services in the window. What remains: verify temporal causality and downstream position using traces — specifically, determine whether ts-order-service latency/disk/cpu spike occurred before the observed drops in auth/route row_count (which might be downstream effects), and inspect trace duration_mean time series for calls to and from these services to identify the most downstream faulty service in traces. This is necessary before declaring the root-cause under the localization rules because multiple service-level anomalies exist.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 04:08:41 → 2024-01-24 04:38:41 UTC. Select only trace_name entries that indicate per-service call durations for the candidate services: any trace_name that contains 'to_ts-order-service.duration_mean' OR 'to_ts-order-service.duration_p95' OR 'to_ts-auth-service.duration_mean' OR 'to_ts-auth-service.duration_p95' OR 'to_ts-route-service.duration_mean' OR 'to_ts-route-service.duration_p95' OR 'to_ts-train-service.duration_mean' OR 'to_ts-train-service.duration_p95' OR 'to_ts-travel-service.duration_mean' OR 'to_ts-travel-service.duration_p95'. For these rows, return up to 200 rows sorted by timestamp with columns: timestamp (as ISO UTC), cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Also return a compact per-trace_name summary (grouped) with: trace_name, count_in_window, first_ts_in_window, last_ts_in_window, min_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, median_value_in_window. Limit the grouped summary to the trace_names found (up to 20). Do not print raw full time series beyond the limited rows requested." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocess and anomaly detection for the five candidate services and inspected traces for service-level durations. Key findings so far: (1) ts-order-service exhibits the largest metric spikes (notably latency-50 with very high relative severity ≈3.8) and has multiple resource anomalies (cpu, diskio) spanning times inside the incident window. (2) ts-auth-service shows large trace durations (trace.to_ts-auth-service.duration_p95 median ~0.51 s and a max ~1.7 s between 04:11–04:17) and decreases in log.row_count (substantial drop). (3) ts-train-service shows many low socket samples and some low cpu/workload samples; ts-route and ts-travel show smaller anomalies. (4) Trace error rates are zero, so we must rely on duration traces and metric timing to determine causality. To localize the root cause we need temporal ordering: which service first showed a significant fault in the incident window, and whether that faulty service is downstream in call chains. The next step is to extract the earliest anomaly occurrence per candidate service (from metrics) to compare times across services and guide downstream selection using trace ordering.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the five candidate services [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] recompute metric anomalies inside the incident window 2024-01-24 04:08:41 → 2024-01-24 04:38:41 UTC using the previously defined global thresholds (P95 and P5 computed on full series). For each service return one row with these columns: cmdb_id, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO UTC), kpi_name_of_earliest_anomaly, anomaly_type_of_earliest_anomaly (high/low), severity_metric_of_earliest_anomaly, count_anomalies_in_window_for_service (sum across all KPIs), and the timestamp_of_max_severity_event_for_service (ISO UTC) where max severity is the largest absolute severity_metric among that service's anomalies. Limit output to these five rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window ascending." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection for the five candidate services. Metric analysis shows ts-order-service as the strongest candidate (largest total anomalies and the highest-severity latency spike around 04:30), while ts-auth-service shows unusually high trace durations (auth p95 max ~1.7s, median ~0.51s) and large drops in log.row_count. All five services had their earliest anomalies at 04:11:00Z, so temporal ordering based solely on first anomaly does not separate them. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level faulty components exist we must use traces to identify the most downstream faulty service in call chains. Therefore the next step is to extract call edges from the trace data within the incident window to determine which candidate services call which others and which of the faulty services appear downstream in traces. This will let us decide whether ts-order-service is downstream (and thus the root cause) or whether ts-auth-service (or another) is downstream and therefore likelier to be root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 04:08:41 → 2024-01-24 04:38:41 UTC. Select rows where the trace_name contains either 'to_ts-' or 'from_ts-' and where either (a) the cmdb_id (source) is one of the five candidates [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] OR (b) the target service extracted from the trace_name (the substring after 'to_' up to the next '.' or end) is one of those five. For each matching row, extract: timestamp (ISO UTC), source_cmdb_id (the cmdb_id column), trace_name, target_service (parsed from trace_name after 'to_'), and value. Then aggregate by (source_cmdb_id, target_service, trace_metric_type) where trace_metric_type is the suffix of trace_name after the target (e.g., 'duration_mean','duration_p95','error_rate','row_count'): compute count_in_window, first_ts_in_window, last_ts_in_window, median_value_in_window. Return two outputs: (1) the aggregated table limited to top 50 rows sorted by count_in_window desc then median_value_in_window desc, with columns source_cmdb_id, target_service, trace_metric_type, count_in_window, first_ts_in_window, last_ts_in_window, median_value_in_window; (2) a compact list of unique source_cmdb_id values and unique target_service values observed among these rows. Do not return full raw time series beyond this aggregation." }

{
    "analysis": "We have applied the preprocess -> anomaly detection -> metric/trace/log analysis workflow focused on the five candidate services. Findings so far: (1) ts-order-service shows the strongest metric faults (largest total anomaly count and the single largest-severity latency spike around 2024-01-24T04:30:00Z). (2) ts-auth-service shows high trace durations (auth duration_p95 median ~0.51s and max ~1.7s between 04:11–04:17) and a pronounced drop in log.row_count (substantial throughput reduction). (3) All five services show anomalies starting at 04:11:00Z, so first-occurrence timing does not separate them; their peak severities occur at different times (auth ~04:13, order ~04:30, train ~04:35). (4) Trace aggregation shows heavy self-traffic and short duration calls from root to the candidate services; call durations toward order/route/train are generally small and stable, while calls toward auth and travel are larger. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level faulty components exist we must identify which faulty service is the most downstream in call chains. To decide between ts-order-service and ts-auth-service (and others), we need to know whether these candidate services call one another (inter-candidate edges) and the relative timing of their anomalous trace durations. Currently we lack a focused trace view of inter-candidate call edges (e.g., ts-auth-service -> ts-order-service or ts-order-service -> ts-auth-service). Determining that will let us identify the downstream faulty service and thus the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously aggregated trace-call data (trace.csv), extract only aggregated call edges where BOTH the source (source_cmdb_id) and the target_service are within the candidate set [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each such edge and each trace_metric_type (duration_mean, duration_p95, row_count, error_rate), return one row with: source_cmdb_id, target_service, trace_metric_type, count_in_window, first_ts_in_window, last_ts_in_window, median_value_in_window, max_value_in_window. Limit results to top 20 rows sorted by count_in_window desc then median_value_in_window desc. If no inter-candidate edges are present, return an explicit empty result indicator." }

